# HyperLink — Environment Variables

Copy this file to `.env.local` (for `apps/web`) and fill in the values.
**Never commit `.env.local` to version control.**

---

## `apps/web/.env.local`

```bash
# ── Supabase ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Your Supabase project URL (Settings → API → Project URL)
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co

# Your Supabase anon/public key (Settings → API → Project API keys → anon public)
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key-here

# ── PeerJS Signaling Server ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Host of the deployed signaling server (no protocol prefix)
NEXT_PUBLIC_PEER_SERVER_HOST=your-signaling-server.onrender.com

# Port (443 for HTTPS in prod, 9000 for local dev)
NEXT_PUBLIC_PEER_SERVER_PORT=443

# Path registered in the PeerJS ExpressPeerServer config
NEXT_PUBLIC_PEER_SERVER_PATH=/myapp

# ── TURN Server (optional) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# If left blank, falls back to public OpenRelay TURN servers.
# For production, use a provider like Metered.ca or Twilio.
TURN_URL=
TURN_USERNAME=
TURN_CREDENTIAL=

# ── Sentry (optional) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Your Sentry DSN for error reporting
SENTRY_DSN=
SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN=
```

---

## `apps/signaling/.env` (or Render environment variables)

```bash
# Port the signaling server listens on
PORT=9000

# Comma-separated list of allowed CORS origins (no wildcards!)
ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000,https://your-domain.com

# Log level: trace | debug | info | warn | error
LOG_LEVEL=info
```

---

## Local Development Quick Start

```bash
# 1. Copy env file
cp .env.example apps/web/.env.local

# 2. Fill in NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL and NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY

# 3. Run migrations against your Supabase project
#    (Supabase Dashboard → SQL Editor, run each file in supabase/migrations/ in order)

# 4. Start dev servers
npm run dev
```
